This article is a presidential proclamation by President Barack Obama declaring February as National Teen Dating Violence Awareness and Prevention Month. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of addressing the issue of violence within relationships during adolescence and highlights the negative consequences it can have on teenagers. It also acknowledges that many young people may be afraid to discuss or recognize the severity of dating violence. The proclamation calls for the promotion of mutual respect and the challenge of unhealthy representations in popular culture. It also mentions the use of technology for control, stalking, and victimization, and encourages concerned individuals to seek help from the National Teen Dating Abuse Helpline. The Department of Justice's Office on Violence Against Women and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention are mentioned as resources for preventing teen dating violence. The proclamation calls on all Americans to support efforts in their communities, schools, and families to empower young people to develop healthy relationships and prevent and respond to dating violence.